tspan.tspan: Given a service description, the Management
and Organization (MANO) validates the service
description and identifies the resources needed
to implement the service and instantiates the
service flow graph. It acomplishes this by
issuing appropriate commands to VNF Manager
and VIM. Authorization using the OSS/BSS and
global resource are also prerformed by the
MANO. Projects: OpenBaton, ONAP (OPEN-O),
OSM, Tacker, Cloudify.
Responsible for the lifecycle management
(creation, configuration, upgrade, teardown) of
NFV services. Provides autoscaling, fault
management, and monitoring of Services. There
may be multiple VNFMs, both open-source and
proprietary depending on the VNF being
managed. The VNFM communicates with the
VNF through the EMS. Projects: Open Baton
Generic VNFM, Juju VNFM, OpenStack Tacker.
ONAP, Cloudify Generic VNFM, Weaver.
Responsible for creation and managment of
virtual infrastructure. A VIM coordiates with
various sub modules to provide Virtual
Computing, Virtual Storage and Virtual
Networking. Elements like SDN controllers
which provide virutal networking are also
assumed to be a part of VIM. Projects:
Openstack, Kubernetes, CloudStack.
The Operations Support Systems/Business
Support Systems are the applications that
enable functionalties like billing, order, call
center automation, customer management and
other back-office applications. These systems
tend to be mostly proprietary and are very
rigid. Integration of OSS/BSS with the newer
NFV infrastructure remains an unsolved
problem.
Describes how a NFV service is constructed.
Lists the various elements in the NFV flow graph
and describes the relationship between
individual components. TOSCA (Topology and
Orchestration Specification for Cloud
Applications) and YANG are two popular data
modeling languages used in the NFV world.
TOSCA is more suited to define cloud
components and YANG is targeted towards
defining network components.
Elemental Management Systems (EMS) provide
the interface between VNF Manager and various
VNFs for the network managment of the given
VNFs. They are responsible for recieiving
commands from the VNFM and configuring the
VNF. There can be one EMS per VNF or for
multiple VNFs.
Isolates the virtual layer from the underlying
hardware. Exposes virtual resources to the VNF
where it can be executed. For performance
reasons, the VNF may be required to have direct
access to the underlying hardware (eg: NICs).
The Virtualization layer is responseible for
exposing it to the VNF without compromizing
the security and isoloation of other VNFs.
Projects: KVM, VMWare, Xen, LXC, Docker
All the hardware and software which build up
the environment in which VNFs are deployed,
managed and executed. Consists of commodity
hardware and white-label switches. There is a
push to make this layer as vendor agnostic as
possible while moving vendor specific elements
into a virtual environment like VMs or
Containers.
Virtualized Network Functions (VNFs) are
network elements that provide a specific
networking functionality. Examples include
Firewall, DNS, LB, NAT, CDN, IMS. VNFs can be
both proprietary (Netscaler) or Opensource
(OVS) and can run either on VMs or Containers.
VNFs can be linked together (service chaining)
to impelement a higher level network service.
